  "prompt": "Are grapes bad for any breeds of dogs?",
  "response": "Yes, grapes (and raisins, which are dried grapes) are toxic to all breeds of dogs. The exact mechanism of toxicity is still unknown, and the amount of grapes that can cause poisoning varies greatly from dog to dog. Some dogs can eat a small amount and be fine, while others can develop kidney failure after ingesting just a few.\n\n**Regardless of breed, grapes and raisins should be avoided entirely.**\n\nWhile some breeds might have anecdotal stories associating them with higher or lower sensitivity, there's no scientific evidence to suggest any particular breed is more or less resistant to grape/raisin toxicity.\n\n**Here's why they're bad and what to do:**\n\n*   **Toxicity:** The toxic agent in grapes/raisins is still undetermined, making it difficult to predict safe dosages.\n*   **Symptoms:** Symptoms can include vomiting, diarrhea, loss of appetite, lethargy, abdominal pain, increased thirst and urination, and eventually kidney failure.\n*   **Severity:** Kidney failure can be fatal if not treated promptly.\n*   **Action:** If you suspect your dog has eaten grapes or raisins, contact your veterinarian or an animal poison control center **immediately**, even if they seem fine. Don't wait for symptoms to appear. Time is of the essence.\n\n**In summary, all dogs are at risk from grape and raisin toxicity, so keep them well out of reach.**",
